## Common Agent Mistakes (Auto-Check)

### Stale Closure Prevention

In any callback, timer, or event handler that references state, always use the functional updater form:

- ✅ `setState(prev => prev + 1)`
- ✅ `setState(prev => [...prev, newItem])`
- ❌ `setState(count + 1)` inside setTimeout, useEffect cleanup, or event listeners
- ❌ `setState([...items, newItem])` inside callbacks that close over `items`

If the callback is passed to `setTimeout`, `setInterval`, `addEventListener`, or a child component's `onX` prop, assume the value is stale — use the functional form.

### Context Value Referential Equality

Every React context provider value must be referentially stable. Creating a new object on every render causes all consumers to re-render — cascading across 30+ screens.

```tsx
// ❌ New object every render — every useContext(AuthContext) consumer re-renders
<AuthContext.Provider value={{ user, signOut, loading }}>

// ✅ Stable reference — consumers only re-render when actual values change
const value = useMemo(() => ({ user, signOut, loading }), [user, signOut, loading])
<AuthContext.Provider value={value}>
```

Apply to: AuthProvider, CreditsProvider, any shared context. This is the #1 cause of unexplained mobile lag in multi-screen apps.

